WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.660
You know, when you look at a highly complex mathematical equation, there is this almost innate expectation of absolute truth.

00:10.860 --> 00:14.720
Right. Yeah, it carries this massive weight of objective reality.

00:14.780 --> 00:19.720
Exactly. It's like you are staring at the underlying source code of the universe or something.

00:19.720 --> 00:30.100
If you see Greek letters, integral signs, you know, partial derivatives, your brain just automatically assumes that whoever wrote this actually figured it out.

00:30.520 --> 00:37.900
I mean, we are heavily conditioned by our education systems to trust the notation itself.

00:38.460 --> 00:43.200
Sometimes even more than the concepts the notation is supposed to represent.

00:43.540 --> 00:44.160
Oh, totally.

00:44.320 --> 00:48.520
Like we see a differential equation and we just think, well, the physics must be sound.

00:48.520 --> 00:56.780
But then you step into the bleeding edge of artificial intelligence, specifically the race to build advanced memory architectures.

00:56.900 --> 01:00.260
And suddenly that comfort completely evaporates.

01:00.300 --> 01:02.140
It really does. It's the Wild West right now.

01:02.200 --> 01:07.520
It is wild. If you are tracking the theoretical landscape of AI right now, you know exactly what I mean.

01:07.840 --> 01:14.700
We are seeing papers packed with beautiful, incredibly dense equations that might actually just be mirages.

01:15.220 --> 01:17.820
Yeah, mathematical mirages. That's a good way to put it.

01:17.820 --> 01:21.180
And that is exactly what we're getting into with you today.

01:21.740 --> 01:23.420
So welcome to the deep dive.

01:24.140 --> 01:32.580
We have an absolutely fascinating, intensely technical source document to explore with you.

01:33.000 --> 01:35.500
It's a really incredible piece of work.

01:35.620 --> 01:41.240
It is. It's a comprehensive paper by an author known only as the Flyxion Independent Researcher.

01:41.240 --> 01:57.560
And what this document does is, well, it essentially executes a brutal teardown and then, incredibly, a brilliant theoretical rescue of an AI memory system called MEM8.

01:57.780 --> 02:03.300
Right. And MEM8 is arguably one of the most fascinating case studies in recent theoretical computer science.

02:03.480 --> 02:08.580
I mean, the original designers claim to have built a wave-based memory architecture.

02:08.580 --> 02:10.340
Which sounds so cool.

02:10.500 --> 02:11.000
It does.

02:11.400 --> 02:21.340
Their proposal was to basically stop treating information like discrete files sitting in a digital directory and start treating memory like interfering rebels in a pond.

02:21.520 --> 02:28.460
Which, I mean, that sounds revolutionary because if you think about how human memory feels, it doesn't feel like opening a PDF, right?

02:28.580 --> 02:29.560
No, not at all.

02:29.560 --> 02:31.880
It feels fluid. It blends.

02:32.880 --> 02:39.100
But as we are about to see, the original designers of MEM8 just kind of faked the map.

02:39.240 --> 02:40.460
They absolutely faked it.

02:40.760 --> 02:42.560
They used the equations as decoration.

02:42.560 --> 02:59.120
But the absolute hook of this whole document, the part that makes this a must-read for anyone in the field, is that while they were faking the math, they accidentally stumbled onto a profound, literal truth about how physical brains actually store memories.

02:59.540 --> 03:01.660
Specifically, female rat brains.

03:01.940 --> 03:07.020
Right. So they basically guessed the right answer using entirely the wrong working.

03:07.020 --> 03:17.760
Exactly. And our goal here is to separate the poetic metaphors of MEM8 from the hardcore computational physics required to actually build it.

03:17.940 --> 03:20.720
We have to translate the poetry into engineering.

03:21.040 --> 03:30.800
Yes. We need to translate these vague, hand-wavy ideas about resonance and waves into an implementable, mathematically rigorous framework.

03:30.800 --> 03:43.360
Okay, let's unpack this. Before we can build this perfect, physically grounded AI memory system with you, we have to look at the wreckage of how MEM8 tried and spectacularly failed to do it.

03:43.780 --> 03:48.460
And this brings up a concept the author introduces that I think everyone needs in their vocabulary.

03:49.040 --> 03:50.800
Oh, motivated formalism.

03:51.600 --> 03:58.800
Yes. Motivated formalism. It is an incredibly dangerous trap in theoretical development.

03:58.800 --> 04:02.280
Break that down for us. What does that actually mean in practice?

04:03.700 --> 04:19.880
So, it's the practice of deploying complex mathematical notation, things like wave equations, partial differential equations, complex exponentials, not to specify a computable process, but simply as an aesthetic choice.

04:20.040 --> 04:22.320
Wait, so just using math to look smart?

04:22.320 --> 04:30.320
Essentially, yeah. It is using the language of physics to lend unearned authority to vague philosophical ideas.

04:31.220 --> 04:38.620
Wow. It's like putting on a doctor's white coat and a stethoscope to look authoritative, but you don't actually know how to diagnose a patient.

04:38.820 --> 04:40.060
That's a perfect analogy.

04:40.220 --> 04:46.400
And wait, I have to clarify something here, because if you read the MEM8 paper, the equations are real equations, right?

04:46.500 --> 04:49.440
Like, they aren't just gibberish symbols drawn at random.

04:49.440 --> 04:52.420
No, they follow standard mathematical syntax.

04:52.620 --> 04:55.080
So, where does the illusion actually fall apart?

04:55.300 --> 04:59.480
The syntax is valid, but the semantic mapping is completely broken.

04:59.540 --> 05:01.000
Okay, I'm going to need an example.

05:01.460 --> 05:09.480
Sure. The illusion falls apart on the bridge between the symbols and the computational reality they supposedly represent.

05:09.480 --> 05:15.460
Let's look at the central equation MEM8 uses to represent a single memory.

05:15.660 --> 05:15.960
Okay.

05:16.300 --> 05:18.320
They format it as an analytic signal.

05:18.800 --> 05:26.320
So, it's psi of t equals a of t times e to the power of i times omega t plus phi.

05:26.460 --> 05:27.560
That is a lot of Greek.

05:27.680 --> 05:32.080
For those of you visualizing this, let's break down what those letters are actually trying to do.

05:32.140 --> 05:36.220
Right. So, in classical physics, this is just a standard way to write out a wave.

05:36.220 --> 05:38.920
A run-and-mo represents amplitude.

05:39.500 --> 05:41.440
Which MEM8 maps to importance, right?

05:41.500 --> 05:45.220
Yes. They attempt to map amplitude to a concept they call importance.

05:46.220 --> 05:47.380
The omega is frequency.

05:47.920 --> 05:52.560
Phi is phase, which they arbitrarily designate as emotional phase.

05:53.300 --> 05:54.320
And it's time.

05:55.420 --> 05:57.660
Okay. So far, it sounds like a literal wave.

05:57.800 --> 05:58.740
So, what's the issue?

05:59.020 --> 06:03.420
Well, here's the first massive structural problem the Flyxion author identifies.

06:03.420 --> 06:05.580
They call it the imaginary problem.

06:05.740 --> 06:06.920
The imaginary problem.

06:07.040 --> 06:07.180
Yeah.

06:07.600 --> 06:15.260
The equation uses Euler's formula, which relies on i, the imaginary unit, the square root of negative one.

06:15.420 --> 06:17.340
Right. From high school algebra.

06:17.780 --> 06:18.240
Exactly.

06:19.080 --> 06:25.780
In physics, using complex exponential representations is an incredibly useful mathematical artifact

06:25.780 --> 06:32.780
for tracking oscillating signals, like electromagnetic fields or fluid dynamics.

06:32.880 --> 06:34.820
Because it lets you track two things at once, right?

06:34.840 --> 06:40.400
Right. You have a real component and an imaginary component, and together, they give you amplitude and phase.

06:40.900 --> 06:44.980
But a semantic memory is not a simple temporal signal.

06:45.240 --> 06:51.600
Right. If you have a memory of reading a specific contract, or a memory of your 10th birthday party,

06:51.600 --> 06:55.660
that isn't a continuous sound wave bouncing around a room.

06:55.660 --> 06:59.700
No. It's a highly structured encoding of semantic content.

06:59.860 --> 07:00.120
Okay.

07:00.640 --> 07:05.360
Therefore, if you represent a semantic memory with a complex valued equation,

07:05.720 --> 07:07.700
you have to answer a fundamental question.

07:08.380 --> 07:11.760
What does the imaginary component actually mean semantically?

07:12.220 --> 07:13.700
Oh. Wow.

07:14.160 --> 07:17.460
What is the square root of negative one of a birthday party?

07:17.460 --> 07:21.160
Exactly. And the MEME documentation never answers this.

07:21.460 --> 07:26.540
They borrowed the notation from signal processing without ever defining the semantic domain.

07:26.640 --> 07:29.380
So they just copy-pasted the math because it looked like a wave.

07:29.600 --> 07:30.220
Pretty much.

07:31.020 --> 07:34.740
And if the memory content only lives in the real part of the equation,

07:35.480 --> 07:40.000
then you mathematically cannot independently recover the emotional phase,

07:40.460 --> 07:45.920
that phi variable, without extra, highly specific extraction procedures.

07:45.920 --> 07:48.400
Procedures that I'm guessing they didn't include.

07:48.720 --> 07:51.820
Procedures that MEME-80 completely fails to specify.

07:52.120 --> 07:55.440
So they put on the doctor's coat, but they don't know how to read the chart.

07:55.880 --> 08:01.120
And honestly, it gets so much worse when we look at omega, the frequency variable.

08:01.380 --> 08:02.680
The frequency arbitrariness.

08:02.920 --> 08:07.480
Right. Because the MEME-8 designers call this the content type frequency.

08:08.000 --> 08:11.540
They claim that different types of memories have different frequencies,

08:11.880 --> 08:13.340
and that's how they interact.

08:13.340 --> 08:17.140
And this is a fatal flaw in their entire interference model.

08:17.940 --> 08:20.220
MEME claims that similar memories resonate,

08:20.540 --> 08:23.220
and different ones interfere based on these frequencies.

08:23.480 --> 08:27.380
Okay, but how do you assign a physical frequency to an idea?

08:27.780 --> 08:28.460
You can't.

08:28.920 --> 08:33.020
How do you assign a scalar frequency to a categorical distinction

08:33.020 --> 08:35.180
without it being entirely arbitrary?

08:35.660 --> 08:38.260
Give us an example of what that means in practice.

08:38.260 --> 08:41.340
Like, if I'm feeding files into this AI.

08:42.060 --> 08:44.080
Let's say you have an AI ingesting data.

08:45.180 --> 08:50.560
What is the intrinsic numerical frequency of a text file versus an image file?

08:50.720 --> 08:51.760
It doesn't have one.

08:51.940 --> 08:52.120
Right.

08:52.560 --> 08:59.040
What is the physical frequency of a PDF of a corporate tax return versus a JPEG of a cat?

08:59.300 --> 09:00.860
You literally just have to make it up.

09:00.860 --> 09:03.380
You have to write a line of code saying,

09:03.380 --> 09:10.480
okay, text files vibrate at 10 hertz, and image files vibrate at 20 hertz.

09:10.680 --> 09:16.640
And if you do that, any mathematical interference you calculate between them is completely meaningless.

09:16.920 --> 09:20.240
Because it's just an artifact of your random numbering system.

09:20.420 --> 09:24.160
It's not a physical truth about how those concepts relate to one another.

09:24.400 --> 09:24.920
Exactly.

09:24.920 --> 09:29.780
The interference structure they boast about isn't a natural consequence of mathematics.

09:30.300 --> 09:36.240
It's a completely fabricated artifact of an unspecified encoding choice.

09:36.640 --> 09:37.880
That is so damning.

09:37.960 --> 09:42.440
And the Flyxion author points out another glaring issue, which they call the Laplacian Void.

09:42.640 --> 09:43.660
Ah, yes.

09:44.240 --> 09:45.380
The Laplacian Void.

09:45.500 --> 09:47.580
It sounds like a terrifying sci-fi concept.

09:47.880 --> 09:49.680
What is it in the context of this math?

09:49.680 --> 09:57.720
So, MEME8 introduces a partial differential equation to describe how these memory waves propagate and interact.

09:58.500 --> 10:02.440
And they use a Laplacian operator, denoted as del squared m.

10:02.840 --> 10:07.240
Okay, for those of us who aren't physics PhDs, what is a Laplacian?

10:07.960 --> 10:13.020
In physics, a Laplacian is used to describe how a quantity changes over a spatial domain.

10:13.020 --> 10:22.460
It measures the difference between the value of a field at a specific point and the average value of the field in the immediate surrounding area.

10:22.880 --> 10:24.820
So, like heat spreading out.

10:24.960 --> 10:25.200
Yes.

10:25.460 --> 10:32.160
We use it to model heat diffusing through a metal plate or waves rippling across the surface of a drum.

10:32.400 --> 10:34.160
So, it requires a spatial domain.

10:34.520 --> 10:41.680
It inherently means the mass needs a physical space or at least a simulated coordinate grid to exist in.

10:41.680 --> 10:43.920
It absolutely implies a geometry.

10:44.480 --> 10:46.540
But MEME8 defines no grid.

10:46.760 --> 10:48.080
Wait, none at all?

10:48.180 --> 10:48.440
None.

10:48.760 --> 10:50.560
They define no spatial boundaries.

10:50.940 --> 10:52.580
They don't outline a topology.

10:52.880 --> 10:54.600
They don't even define a wave speed.

10:54.680 --> 10:56.460
Those are just floating in nothingness.

10:56.740 --> 11:00.620
It is a partial differential equation floating in an absolute void.

11:00.780 --> 11:01.000
Wow.

11:01.060 --> 11:05.800
It is perfectly coherent as a dynamical system on a theoretical whiteboard.

11:05.800 --> 11:12.480
But without defining the computational grid it runs on, the equation cannot be computed.

11:12.680 --> 11:16.000
Because you literally have no space to run the math in.

11:16.120 --> 11:16.360
Right.

11:16.860 --> 11:19.420
You can't feed it into a matrix solver.

11:19.660 --> 11:24.240
It is literally mathematically useless for a software engineer.

11:24.240 --> 11:28.860
This raises an important question for me, and I'm sure for you listening right now.

11:29.000 --> 11:40.400
If the math is just an aesthetic template, this motivated formalism full of undefined variables, arbitrary mappings, and uncomputable voids.

11:40.720 --> 11:41.960
Why are we talking about it?

11:42.040 --> 11:42.340
Yeah.

11:42.580 --> 11:42.780
Yeah.

11:42.780 --> 11:45.080
Why are we dedicating a deep dive to this?

11:45.180 --> 11:49.560
Why didn't the Flyxion author just throw the entire memate paper in the trash and move on?

11:49.780 --> 11:56.560
Because the underlying philosophy, the intuition driving those broken equations, is actually profound.

11:56.880 --> 11:57.200
Okay.

11:57.400 --> 11:58.060
What did they get right?

11:58.480 --> 12:01.900
Memate assumes that memory is defined by time.

12:02.540 --> 12:06.300
It assumes that the temporal structure of an experience is what gives it meaning.

12:06.300 --> 12:14.560
And crucially, it assumes that retrieving a memory isn't just looking up a static file in a directory.

12:15.100 --> 12:16.780
It's not just pulling a book off a shelf.

12:16.880 --> 12:20.020
No, it's a dynamic reconstruction of past constraints.

12:20.340 --> 12:21.780
So it's an active process.

12:21.960 --> 12:22.180
Yes.

12:22.460 --> 12:31.000
And that philosophy connects to very real, very rigorous traditions in compressed sensing and variational inference.

12:31.820 --> 12:35.400
The destination memate gestured toward is exactly right.

12:35.400 --> 12:40.460
They just lacked the theoretical infrastructure to actually build the vehicle to get there.

12:40.780 --> 12:41.160
Precisely.

12:41.400 --> 12:50.640
So to prove that this destination, this idea of a continuous wave-based memory system, isn't just a complete fantasy.

12:50.760 --> 12:51.960
The author does something brilliant.

12:52.180 --> 12:52.780
They pivot.

12:53.200 --> 12:53.960
A huge pivot.

12:54.120 --> 12:54.360
Yeah.

12:54.560 --> 12:59.140
They transition entirely from the failed, hollow equations of memate,

12:59.140 --> 13:06.260
and they point us toward a physical system where wave-based memory actually exists and functions perfectly.

13:06.520 --> 13:10.140
We move from the illusion of math to the biological blueprint.

13:10.480 --> 13:11.660
The mammalian brain.

13:11.720 --> 13:12.740
The mammalian brain.

13:12.800 --> 13:21.140
And the author grounds this entire theoretical rescue mission in a highly specific 2023 study by Cabral et al.

13:21.140 --> 13:26.780
And this study involves ultra-fast fMRI scans of female rat brains.

13:26.780 --> 13:29.120
Yes, and this is where the theory becomes tangible.

13:29.420 --> 13:30.560
Let's get into the biology.

13:30.940 --> 13:33.260
Because honestly, this study blew my mind.

13:33.720 --> 13:37.400
It's the crucial empirical anchor for the entire Flyxion paper.

13:38.420 --> 13:45.720
It basically proves that the wave-based memory intuition has a non-metaphorical physical instantiation.

13:46.140 --> 13:48.380
Meaning it actually happens in the real world.

13:48.380 --> 13:49.100
Exactly.

13:49.400 --> 13:54.100
The Cabral study demonstrates that spontaneous macroscale activity in the brain

13:54.100 --> 14:00.280
naturally organizes into a discrete repertoire of intrinsic oscillatory modes.

14:00.400 --> 14:03.660
Okay, intrinsic macroscale oscillatory modes.

14:04.300 --> 14:07.040
If you aren't a neuroscientist, let's translate that,

14:07.880 --> 14:12.200
the brain's activity naturally forms literal physical waves.

14:12.280 --> 14:13.040
Physical waves.

14:13.640 --> 14:16.240
And the mathematics here are vital to understand.

14:16.300 --> 14:17.320
Work is down for us.

14:17.320 --> 14:25.520
So the fMRI signal measures blood oxygenation across thousands of 20 3D pixels, which are called voxels.

14:25.680 --> 14:26.980
Right, 3D pixels.

14:27.220 --> 14:30.960
And the researchers found that the activity across these thousands of voxels

14:30.960 --> 14:34.700
decomposes mathematically into what are called eigenmodes.

14:35.260 --> 14:35.740
Eigenmodes.

14:36.080 --> 14:40.620
Okay, if we think about this acoustically, is this like the harmonics on a guitar string?

14:40.820 --> 14:42.140
That is the perfect analogy.

14:42.140 --> 14:47.780
When you pluck a guitar string, it doesn't just vibrate in random, chaotic static.

14:48.020 --> 14:50.060
It vibrates at specific frequencies.

14:50.660 --> 14:50.980
Right.

14:51.600 --> 14:55.760
The physical boundaries of the string, where it is pinned at the bridge,

14:56.120 --> 15:00.540
and the nut force it to vibrate at specific, fundamental frequencies,

15:00.960 --> 15:03.280
and their mathematically related harmonics.

15:03.280 --> 15:06.020
Because it physically can't vibrate any other way.

15:06.180 --> 15:06.700
Exactly.

15:07.760 --> 15:11.320
Those stable patterns of vibration are its eigenmodes.

15:12.380 --> 15:17.660
The rat brain, because of its physical connective geometry, its dense white matter tracks,

15:17.800 --> 15:25.020
its cortical soles, the literal shape of the skull, acts like a complex three-dimensional instrument.

15:25.020 --> 15:30.160
So, the electrical and chemical activity flowing through the brain can't just move randomly.

15:30.420 --> 15:30.680
No.

15:30.860 --> 15:38.280
The physical structure of the brain forces that activity to fall into these specific, predictable spatial patterns.

15:38.560 --> 15:38.800
Yes.

15:39.800 --> 15:44.420
These eigenmodes are actual spatial patterns with specific temporal signatures.

15:44.980 --> 15:50.660
And the study shows these temporal signatures follow what are known in dynamical systems theory

15:50.660 --> 15:53.440
as underdamped Stuart-Landau equations.

15:53.440 --> 15:56.400
Okay, you're going to have to break down the Stuart-Landau equation for us.

15:56.460 --> 15:59.040
Why is that specific equation important here?

15:59.200 --> 16:04.220
It's important because it describes a system operating just below what's called a Hoff bifurcation.

16:04.480 --> 16:06.360
A Hoff bifurcation.

16:06.540 --> 16:07.180
What's that?

16:07.640 --> 16:15.500
It's the mathematical tipping point, where a system goes from resting at a stable equilibrium point

16:15.500 --> 16:19.480
to continuously oscillating in a loop, like a pendulum.

16:19.760 --> 16:20.460
Oh, I see.

16:20.460 --> 16:27.400
Because the brain operates just below this tipping point, the waves are intrinsically oscillatory.

16:27.720 --> 16:33.960
They want a wave, but they're underdamped, meaning they eventually damp out over time.

16:34.160 --> 16:36.300
So, they don't just echo forever.

16:36.660 --> 16:36.940
Right.

16:37.280 --> 16:41.400
If you map them mathematically, they show spiral sink phase portraits.

16:41.740 --> 16:48.060
Meaning the waves fade out, like ripples on a pond, eventually settling back to glass.

16:48.060 --> 16:51.520
They don't trap the brain in an endless loop of a single thought.

16:52.340 --> 16:56.280
But here is where the biology gets genuinely mind-bending for me.

16:57.220 --> 17:03.060
How do physical states, like the chemical environment of the brain, affect these biological waves?

17:03.380 --> 17:07.700
Because the author spends a lot of time talking about anesthesia states in these rats.

17:07.760 --> 17:11.460
And this is perhaps the most fascinating piece of empirical evidence in the paper.

17:11.460 --> 17:16.860
However, the researchers altered the biophysical state of the brain using different anesthetics.

17:16.940 --> 17:17.260
Okay.

17:17.680 --> 17:26.500
When the rats were placed under mid-atomidine sedation, the brain maintained approximately 10 distinct resolvable eigenmodes.

17:26.940 --> 17:30.160
10 separate harmonic frequencies playing together.

17:30.280 --> 17:32.700
Right, juggling the complex activity of the brain.

17:32.800 --> 17:35.840
10 complex wave patterns keeping the system running.

17:35.840 --> 17:38.760
But then they changed the drug, right?

17:38.960 --> 17:39.200
Yes.

17:39.560 --> 17:46.280
When they increased the depth of anesthesia using isoflurane, the entire dynamic landscape shifted.

17:46.480 --> 17:47.020
What happened?

17:47.240 --> 17:58.100
The peak frequencies lowered, the mode count dropped, and under deep anesthesia, the entire system collapsed into a single aperiodic global mode.

17:58.180 --> 17:58.640
Oh!

17:58.640 --> 18:07.000
The 10 distinct dancing harmonics merged into one blunt, non-oscillating hum.

18:07.280 --> 18:17.400
Okay, this is incredible, because if you think about it, this shows that the wave description of the brain isn't just a mathematical trick we use to graph fMRI data.

18:17.500 --> 18:18.180
No, it's real.

18:18.340 --> 18:21.860
The biological brain actually earns its wave description.

18:21.860 --> 18:28.880
When MEM-8 talks about massive memory compression, it's treating it like an engineering algorithm, right?

18:29.000 --> 18:30.780
Like zipping a file on your desktop.

18:30.960 --> 18:32.580
Yes, as a software process.

18:32.840 --> 18:37.740
But in the rat brain, the compression is intrinsic to the physics.

18:37.740 --> 18:53.040
You have over 1,400 fMRI voxels, 1,400 discrete points of data, and the literal physics of the tissue naturally rank reduces that down to just 10 essential modes.

18:53.140 --> 18:54.560
Because of the shape of the instrument.

18:54.780 --> 18:55.100
Right.

18:55.100 --> 19:11.760
It's like the difference between violently crushing a car into a tiny cube using an industrial trash compactor, versus the car naturally, elegantly dissolving down into its 10 essential atomic components, because you altered the rules of physics in the room.

19:11.880 --> 19:13.100
That is exactly it.

19:13.300 --> 19:19.440
The compression ratio in the biological brain is a property of the field dynamics themselves.

19:19.940 --> 19:23.340
It's not an arbitrary engineering choice imposed from the outside.

19:23.340 --> 19:25.620
It's just how the physics behave.

19:25.760 --> 19:26.040
Yes.

19:26.720 --> 19:37.980
The effective dimensionality of the system, the number of variables you actually need to describe its state, is far below its representational dimensionality, which is those 1,400 voxels.

19:37.980 --> 19:42.100
So what is the big takeaway here for our AI memory system?

19:42.240 --> 19:47.020
Because we obviously aren't going to culture rat neurons in a vat and plug them into a server rack.

19:47.140 --> 19:47.960
Hopefully not.

19:48.080 --> 19:48.420
Right.

19:48.580 --> 19:52.280
And we can't copy the literal geometry of a rat brain into silicon.

19:52.280 --> 19:56.160
We can't copy the geometry, and we don't need to.

19:57.180 --> 20:01.480
The biological eigenmodes are specific to the biological substrate.

20:01.600 --> 20:01.880
Okay.

20:02.360 --> 20:05.920
But what the rat brain provides is an existence proof.

20:05.920 --> 20:17.200
It proves that wave-based memory, constructive and destructive interference, and intrinsic low-ranked compression are physically, mathematically possible.

20:17.380 --> 20:18.500
They exist in the universe.

20:19.000 --> 20:23.840
They work in reality, provided you build the correct mathematical substrate to support them.

20:23.940 --> 20:25.360
So that is our mission.

20:25.620 --> 20:28.080
We have the proof that it can work in wet tissue.

20:28.080 --> 20:35.260
Now, how do we replace MemMate's broken, floating metaphors with actual computational physics?

20:35.400 --> 20:37.400
How do we build that artificial substrate?

20:37.600 --> 20:38.120
Exactly.

20:38.400 --> 20:44.660
And the Flyxion author outlines three specific, hardcore, theoretical fixes to get us there.

20:44.780 --> 20:45.740
Let's walk through them.

20:45.740 --> 20:51.080
Let's start with the first fix, which fundamentally addresses the concept of time.

20:51.500 --> 20:59.380
We need to move from MemMate's vague idea of temporal tracking to a rigorous concept called trajectory indexing.

20:59.500 --> 21:06.220
Right, because MemMate correctly identified that a memory isn't just a record of what happened, but when and how it happened.

21:06.740 --> 21:08.340
The sequence of events matters.

21:08.340 --> 21:15.240
But their math for doing that was literally just multiplying the signal by T, the time variable.

21:15.280 --> 21:16.580
Which feels a bit lazy.

21:16.760 --> 21:20.000
It is wildly insufficient for a dynamical system.

21:20.340 --> 21:21.100
Fix this.

21:21.620 --> 21:24.700
The author introduces the RSVP framework.

21:25.060 --> 21:28.140
The relativistic scalar vector plenum.

21:28.200 --> 21:28.460
Yes.

21:29.060 --> 21:33.780
And alongside it, a specific trajectory tracking system called Yarncrawler.

21:34.260 --> 21:36.320
Yarncrawler, I love that name.

21:36.420 --> 21:37.500
It's very evocative.

21:37.500 --> 21:41.640
In the RSVP framework, memory is not a static record.

21:42.260 --> 21:44.520
It is not a snapshot saved to a hard drive.

21:44.860 --> 21:47.880
It is an irreversible trajectory encoding.

21:48.700 --> 21:50.320
Irreversible trajectory encoding.

21:50.420 --> 21:51.220
Let's ground that.

21:51.560 --> 21:56.200
If I'm understanding this right, memory isn't a photograph of a room you walked into.

21:56.420 --> 21:56.680
No.

21:56.980 --> 22:03.780
It's the mathematical constraint of the muddy footprints showing the exact path of how you walked into the room.

22:03.900 --> 22:06.200
That is a brilliant way to visualize it.

22:06.200 --> 22:06.760
Yeah.

22:06.760 --> 22:09.000
You are not storing the final state of the system.

22:09.080 --> 22:09.280
Yeah.

22:09.420 --> 22:16.020
You are storing the minimal set of constraints, the muddy footprints, required to reconstruct the path that generated that state.

22:16.260 --> 22:16.600
Okay.

22:16.600 --> 22:21.000
And crucially, as the term says, it is irreversible.

22:21.320 --> 22:24.620
The RSVP framework uses an irreversibility kernel.

22:24.620 --> 22:28.160
Wait, why is irreversibility a feature and not a bug?

22:28.800 --> 22:33.500
If I want perfect recall, shouldn't I be able to reverse the math perfectly?

22:33.500 --> 22:36.060
In a simple, closed system, yes.

22:37.160 --> 22:44.000
But an AI interacting with the real world is an open, continuously evolving system.

22:44.140 --> 22:45.660
Okay, so things are always changing.

22:46.340 --> 22:46.820
Exactly.

22:47.380 --> 22:55.080
The irreversibility kernel means you cannot simply run the equation backward to perfectly recover the exact state of the past.

22:55.320 --> 22:58.480
The history of the system heavily weights its current state.

22:58.480 --> 23:00.320
Because it's moving forward in time.

23:00.320 --> 23:03.840
It is dynamically evolving and time dependent.

23:04.260 --> 23:08.180
The muddy footprints dry, they fade, they get walked over by new footprints.

23:08.380 --> 23:09.740
Oh, that makes so much sense.

23:09.820 --> 23:15.720
It's a residue of an experience, optimized for future utility, not a perfect sterile recording.

23:15.720 --> 23:17.340
Okay, that's the first fix.

23:17.720 --> 23:22.000
Replacing static snapshots with irreversible trajectory indexing.

23:22.480 --> 23:23.680
What is the second fix?

23:24.080 --> 23:28.000
The second fix tackles the absolute core of Mem8's identity.

23:28.720 --> 23:30.280
Resonance and interference.

23:30.700 --> 23:38.360
Right, because Mem8 built their whole brand on the claim that similar memories resonate and conflicting ones destructively interfere.

23:38.960 --> 23:41.780
Like actual water waves crashing into each other.

23:41.780 --> 23:51.620
But as we established in the teardown, without a defined spatial domain or a non-arbitrary frequency mapping, that was purely metaphorical.

23:51.680 --> 23:51.960
Right.

23:52.080 --> 23:58.960
If we can't just arbitrarily assign 10 hertz to a text file, how do we make interference real in the math?

23:59.540 --> 24:02.980
We discard the literal wave metaphor entirely.

24:03.400 --> 24:06.780
We translate it into the language of xylomorphic computation.

24:08.260 --> 24:08.780
Xylomorphic computation.

24:08.780 --> 24:15.060
So we stop talking about waves crashing and start talking about constraint composition and entropy closure.

24:15.340 --> 24:17.780
I am definitely going to need you to walk me through those terms.

24:18.260 --> 24:19.380
Xylomorphic computation.

24:19.880 --> 24:20.680
Entropy closure.

24:21.180 --> 24:22.900
I actually want to push back on this a little bit.

24:22.980 --> 24:23.420
Go for it.

24:23.600 --> 24:30.940
When you say constraint composition, isn't that just a fancy academic way of describing standard traditional logic?

24:30.940 --> 24:34.780
Like an if-then statement in a standard SQL database?

24:35.780 --> 24:40.340
How is entropy closure actually any different than traditional computing?

24:40.860 --> 24:43.260
That's a fair question, but it's a crucial distinction.

24:44.240 --> 24:47.180
Traditional symbolic logic operates discreetly.

24:48.020 --> 24:52.040
If A is true and B is true, then C.

24:52.280 --> 24:52.800
It's binary.

24:53.220 --> 24:53.520
Yes.

24:54.580 --> 24:58.280
Xylomorphic computation operates on continuous fields.

24:58.280 --> 25:07.280
Imagine every memory, not as a string of text, but as a set of logical constraints applied to a topological space.

25:07.400 --> 25:08.660
Okay, I'm picturing it.

25:08.800 --> 25:17.280
If two memories are highly related, say a memory of a dog and a memory of a leash, their constraint sets are mathematically compatible.

25:17.280 --> 25:24.300
They can easily exist in the same minimal entropy state without contradicting each other.

25:24.420 --> 25:25.200
They fit together.

25:25.420 --> 25:25.720
Yes.

25:26.340 --> 25:29.020
In xylomorphic terms, they achieve entropy closure.

25:29.800 --> 25:34.920
Because they can combine smoothly, they naturally reinforce each other in the field.

25:35.060 --> 25:35.640
Oh, wow.

25:35.800 --> 25:42.640
This is the true computable mathematical mechanism behind what Mem 8 poetically called resonance.

25:42.640 --> 25:46.100
Okay, so resonance isn't frequency is vibrating together.

25:46.380 --> 25:49.700
Resonance is just constraint compatibility within a field.

25:49.880 --> 25:50.340
Exactly.

25:50.880 --> 25:54.680
And destructive interference is simply the failure of entropy closure.

25:55.060 --> 25:56.760
Give me an example of that failure.

25:57.200 --> 26:01.140
Let's say you have an established memory constraint that states the sky is blue.

26:01.900 --> 26:05.880
Now a new input enters the system claiming the sky is neon green.

26:05.980 --> 26:06.860
Okay, those don't fit.

26:06.860 --> 26:13.500
Those two constraint sets cannot mathematically exist in the same minimal entropy state.

26:14.200 --> 26:14.900
They contradict.

26:15.600 --> 26:19.200
They cannot be composed without violating their core parameters.

26:19.200 --> 26:21.640
So they destructively interfere.

26:22.000 --> 26:26.360
Not because they are magical, mystical waves oscillating at opposite frequencies,

26:26.620 --> 26:32.200
but just through pure, rigorous constraint logic mapped onto a field.

26:32.400 --> 26:32.660
Right.

26:32.820 --> 26:36.060
The new input forces a higher entropy state.

26:36.060 --> 26:42.100
The field rejects it, and the amplitude of that specific feature cancels out.

26:42.400 --> 26:46.060
You don't need a wave metaphor to achieve the result Mem 8 wanted.

26:46.300 --> 26:50.820
You just need a measurable degree of compatibility between constraint sets.

26:50.980 --> 26:52.640
It's all just constraint logic.

26:52.760 --> 26:54.380
That makes an incredible amount of sense.

26:54.540 --> 26:54.800
Oh.

26:55.300 --> 26:56.820
Okay, on to the third fix.

26:56.980 --> 26:58.620
This one is all about compression,

26:59.280 --> 27:04.780
because Mem 8 heavily promoted this massive 100 to 1 compression ratio.

27:04.780 --> 27:06.460
Oh, yes, they love that number.

27:06.560 --> 27:11.800
They claim that they could shrink memories by a factor of 100 without losing any semantic meaning.

27:12.300 --> 27:14.080
And as the Flyxion author pointed out,

27:14.460 --> 27:18.040
without a formal metric for what constitutes semantic loss,

27:18.480 --> 27:21.060
that claim is mathematically meaningless.

27:21.740 --> 27:25.540
It's an aspirational heuristic, a marketing bullet point.

27:25.940 --> 27:27.800
It's not a measurable benchmark.

27:27.800 --> 27:31.260
Right, because how do you measure the loss of meaning?

27:31.760 --> 27:35.460
Meaning is entirely subjective based on who is asking the question.

27:35.660 --> 27:36.220
Exactly.

27:36.560 --> 27:41.160
So how does the RSVP framework actually fix the concept of compression?

27:41.700 --> 27:47.260
What's fascinating here is how RSVP redefines the very purpose and definition of compression.

27:47.260 --> 27:53.160
It shifts the paradigm away from approximation and toward constraint projection.

27:53.420 --> 27:54.540
Constraint projection.

27:54.800 --> 27:55.080
Yes.

27:55.440 --> 27:58.960
In standard compression like making a JPEG file smaller,

27:59.200 --> 28:00.580
you throw away pixels.

28:01.120 --> 28:07.220
You degrade the absolute fidelity of the image uniformly across the board to save file space.

28:07.600 --> 28:07.840
Right.

28:07.940 --> 28:10.020
The whole image just gets a little blurrier.

28:10.200 --> 28:10.460
Yes.

28:10.460 --> 28:16.280
But in the RSVP framework, compression isn't about degrading the record uniformly.

28:16.880 --> 28:21.620
It is about projecting the memory onto a specific mathematical subspace

28:21.620 --> 28:24.480
based entirely on how you intend to use it.

28:24.580 --> 28:25.760
I need an example of that.

28:26.000 --> 28:29.320
How do you compress something based on use rather than content?

28:29.800 --> 28:33.540
Think of a memory of a dense 50-page complex legal document.

28:33.540 --> 28:37.340
If the AI system only ever plans to query that memory

28:37.340 --> 28:40.200
to retrieve the final financial settlement amount,

28:40.460 --> 28:47.180
the system doesn't need to maintain the constraints that encode the thousands of words of preamble

28:47.180 --> 28:50.260
or the specific formatting of the paragraphs.

28:50.460 --> 28:52.440
Because it's never going to need that formatting.

28:52.680 --> 28:53.140
Exactly.

28:53.700 --> 28:56.540
It mathematically projects the memory down.

28:56.680 --> 28:58.080
It rank reduces it,

28:58.420 --> 29:03.040
keeping only the constraints necessary to answer that specific future question.

29:03.040 --> 29:08.080
You only keep the constraints necessary for the specific questions you plan to ask the memory.

29:08.080 --> 29:14.560
Oh, so compression becomes a dynamic function of utility, not a static function of storage.

29:14.800 --> 29:15.200
Yes.

29:15.200 --> 29:21.020
The same 50-page document might be aggressively compressed down to a single integer

29:21.020 --> 29:25.100
if you only need to answer a simple yes-no question about the settlement.

29:25.600 --> 29:29.740
But that same document would require near lossless encoding

29:29.740 --> 29:36.420
if the system anticipates needing to query the subtle legal maneuvering in the language.

29:36.420 --> 29:39.420
That is the essence of constraint projection.

29:39.560 --> 29:39.760
Yeah.

29:40.080 --> 29:43.260
And understanding that dynamic projection is absolutely necessary

29:43.260 --> 29:49.500
before we tackle the most complex and historically ambiguous element of Mem8's architecture.

29:49.580 --> 29:50.220
Which is?

29:50.260 --> 29:50.660
Emotion.

29:50.740 --> 29:51.180
Oh, yes.

29:51.800 --> 29:53.780
Section four of the teardown.

29:54.420 --> 29:57.140
The geometry of emotion and time.

29:57.140 --> 30:04.360
The designers of Mem8 were obsessed with giving this AI an emotional context field, weren't they?

30:04.420 --> 30:05.240
They really were.

30:05.240 --> 30:12.320
They really wanted this machine memory system to feel or at least simulate the computational weight of feeling.

30:12.980 --> 30:18.300
But as the author shows, their math for implementing emotion was a total disaster.

30:18.300 --> 30:22.600
It was profoundly flawed from a structural standpoint.

30:23.140 --> 30:28.140
Mem8 tried to make emotion dictate everything in the equation simultaneously.

30:28.400 --> 30:30.140
Like pushing all the buttons at once.

30:30.360 --> 30:30.980
Pretty much.

30:31.420 --> 30:34.600
They had the emotional field modulating the phase of the wave

30:34.600 --> 30:38.220
or also adjusting the amplitude or importance of the memory

30:38.220 --> 30:41.000
while simultaneously shifting the frequency.

30:41.220 --> 30:43.140
Which mathematically means what?

30:43.220 --> 30:46.000
If you change all three variables at once, what happened?

30:46.000 --> 30:51.820
It means the entire system becomes overdetermined and fundamentally impossible to reverse engineer.

30:51.960 --> 30:53.300
Walk us through why.

30:53.600 --> 31:00.840
If a strong emotional valence, say extreme fear, shifts the phase, the frequency, and the amplitude

31:00.840 --> 31:07.220
all at the exact same time, then when you attempt to retrieve and read the final memory wave,

31:07.780 --> 31:13.560
you have no way to untangle which mathematical changes came from the actual semantic content

31:13.560 --> 31:15.340
and which came from the emotion.

31:15.340 --> 31:18.000
You can't separate the fear from the facts.

31:18.100 --> 31:18.520
Exactly.

31:18.840 --> 31:24.140
If you have two memories with identical semantic content but totally different emotional valences,

31:24.760 --> 31:29.920
they would destructively interfere in completely unpredictable, chaotic ways.

31:30.480 --> 31:32.440
It destroys the integrity of the data.

31:32.700 --> 31:38.580
It's like you can't bake a cake and then try to extract the eggs, the flour, and the sugar perfectly intact

31:38.580 --> 31:42.200
if you've blended them all into every single variable of the batter.

31:42.420 --> 31:43.760
That's a great way to think about it.

31:43.760 --> 31:47.940
So how does the RSVP framework handle emotion?

31:48.520 --> 31:50.600
Because we know biology does it.

31:50.720 --> 31:54.380
You and I know that our emotions absolutely color our memories.

31:55.140 --> 31:59.100
Fear burns a memory into your brain differently than joy does.

31:59.320 --> 32:06.100
RSVP solves this elegantly by moving away from signal modulation and using a geometric concept

32:06.100 --> 32:07.360
called foliation.

32:07.360 --> 32:08.360
Foliation.

32:08.360 --> 32:13.940
Instead of treating emotion as a volume knob or a frequency dial that actively warps the

32:13.940 --> 32:22.160
memory wave itself, RSVP treats emotion as a submanifold of the broader plenum state space.

32:22.160 --> 32:25.540
Okay, I'm going to need an analogy for a submanifold.

32:25.960 --> 32:31.580
If the plenum state space is the whole environment, what is a submanifold?

32:31.720 --> 32:38.880
Imagine the entire memory system, the plenum state space, as a massive multi-story library.

32:39.000 --> 32:40.700
Okay, got the library in my head.

32:40.700 --> 32:46.700
Mehmet's approach to emotion was like taking a sad memory and painting the book blue, and

32:46.700 --> 32:48.960
taking a happy memory and painting it yellow.

32:49.480 --> 32:51.920
But you put them all on the exact same shelf.

32:52.040 --> 32:53.240
Oh, I see where this is going.

32:53.560 --> 32:58.900
Over time, the colors bleed into each other, the blue paint smears onto the yellow books,

32:59.120 --> 33:01.260
and eventually you can't read the title.

33:01.340 --> 33:02.400
Right, they interfere.

33:02.560 --> 33:04.000
The system is overdetermined.

33:04.000 --> 33:09.540
The RSVP foliation approach says that sadness isn't a color painted onto the book.

33:10.400 --> 33:14.000
Sadness is an entirely different room in the geometry of the library.

33:14.480 --> 33:16.580
It is a distinct submanifold.

33:18.020 --> 33:24.900
When the system encodes a memory under the context of sadness, you are mathematically projecting

33:24.900 --> 33:27.680
that memory into that specific room.

33:28.080 --> 33:32.240
The architecture of the room itself represents the emotional constraint.

33:32.240 --> 33:34.200
Oh, that is absolutely brilliant.

33:34.860 --> 33:38.580
Sadness is an entirely different room in the geometry of the mind.

33:38.940 --> 33:43.140
So the memory exists purely in that restricted space.

33:43.400 --> 33:43.600
Yes.

33:43.760 --> 33:49.620
And if the AI wants to retrieve a sad memory, it doesn't have to apply some weird mathematical

33:49.620 --> 33:52.980
filter to untangle the blue paint from the yellow paint.

33:53.340 --> 33:54.940
It just goes to the sad room.

33:55.140 --> 33:58.360
You restrict your query to that specific submanifold.

33:58.360 --> 34:04.260
The interference between memories is governed by the topological distance between those submanifolds

34:04.260 --> 34:09.120
in the ambient space, not by arbitrarily tweaking individual wave parameters.

34:09.680 --> 34:14.040
The emotional structure is built directly into the geometry of the space itself.

34:14.200 --> 34:16.980
And wait, this ties perfectly back to the biological proof.

34:17.100 --> 34:19.220
The rat brains from the Cabral study.

34:19.220 --> 34:24.940
When they gave the rats different anesthetics, they weren't changing the frequency dials of

34:24.940 --> 34:25.740
the brain waves.

34:26.240 --> 34:29.180
They were changing the biophysical state of the medium.

34:29.660 --> 34:35.760
They were literally restricting which rooms or submanifolds were dynamically accessible

34:35.760 --> 34:37.960
to the brain's baseline activity.

34:38.120 --> 34:39.540
You've connected the dots perfectly.

34:40.060 --> 34:45.260
The anesthesia fundamentally altered the geometry of the accessible state space.

34:45.260 --> 34:50.760
That is non-metaphorical emotional modulation operating at the physical level.

34:51.440 --> 34:55.200
And foliation provides the mathematical equivalent for an AI.

34:55.700 --> 34:57.420
That is just incredible.

34:57.620 --> 35:00.320
Okay, so we have the geometry of emotion figured out.

35:00.540 --> 35:04.940
But we also need to talk about the flow of time during the actual moment of encoding.

35:05.340 --> 35:08.820
Because Memmei had this really interesting idea about reading rates.

35:09.380 --> 35:10.660
Yes, the reading rates.

35:10.660 --> 35:16.700
They suggested that the system encodes a document over time based on how it naturally pauses at

35:16.700 --> 35:23.100
chapter boundaries, or if it experiences an emotional delay while processing a particularly

35:23.100 --> 35:24.660
complex concept.

35:24.800 --> 35:26.940
Yes, the temporal encoding operator.

35:27.480 --> 35:33.140
Memmei mapped this as a function, t of x, generating a time-parameterized signal based

35:33.140 --> 35:34.360
on ingestion speed.

35:35.140 --> 35:37.400
But again, their formalism failed.

35:37.520 --> 35:39.160
They didn't finish the thought.

35:39.160 --> 35:39.760
Right.

35:40.020 --> 35:46.280
They just generated a signal without ever explaining how that temporal signal actually integrates

35:46.280 --> 35:49.080
into the memory field to cause a lasting change.

35:49.460 --> 35:55.100
So how does the RSVP framework integrate the flow of time into the field?

35:55.380 --> 35:59.200
Through what the Flyxion author calls the plenum excitation operator.

35:59.840 --> 36:03.280
This is where the heavy computational physics finally comes into play.

36:03.280 --> 36:09.440
The system takes that temporal signal, the pacing, the pauses, the dynamic flow of the input data,

36:09.660 --> 36:14.060
and feeds it into a continuous, constrained optimization problem.

36:14.340 --> 36:16.260
What exactly is it optimizing?

36:16.820 --> 36:23.240
It is balancing two constantly competing forces, which are defined by the system's Lagrangian.

36:23.400 --> 36:24.480
Oh, Lagrangian.

36:24.480 --> 36:31.220
In physics, a Lagrangian is essentially the master equation that dictates the dynamic evolution of a system.

36:31.860 --> 36:35.060
It summarizes the system's kinetic and potential energy.

36:35.280 --> 36:38.020
Okay, so it's the rules of the road for the physics.

36:38.200 --> 36:38.640
Exactly.

36:39.200 --> 36:46.780
In RSVP, the optimization process is balancing the need to respect the raw informational fidelity of the incoming data

36:46.780 --> 36:52.800
against the necessity of obeying the dynamic physical laws of the plenum field itself.

36:53.320 --> 36:57.560
So it's like, if you are throwing a rock into a pond,

36:58.560 --> 37:01.860
this splash has to represent the size and shape of the rock.

37:01.940 --> 37:05.740
That's the information fidelity, the data of the rock itself.

37:05.840 --> 37:06.060
Right.

37:06.060 --> 37:11.020
But the splash also absolutely has to obey the fluid dynamics of the water.

37:11.160 --> 37:12.200
That's the Lagrangian.

37:12.200 --> 37:19.900
The final wave pattern, the memory, is the optimal compromise between the shape of the rock and the physics of the water.

37:20.040 --> 37:21.820
That is an excellent visualization.

37:22.660 --> 37:28.800
And compression, which we discussed earlier, is the natural mathematical consequence of that optimization.

37:29.880 --> 37:33.940
The memory naturally settles into the lowest rank excitation

37:33.940 --> 37:40.320
that simultaneously satisfies both the data constraints of the rock and the physical constraints of the water.

37:40.320 --> 37:44.620
Okay, this architecture is feeling incredibly solid now.

37:45.340 --> 37:51.960
We have successfully replaced all the floating metaphors with hardcore geometry, constraint logic, and optimization physics.

37:52.420 --> 37:56.820
We have designed the perfect artificial physics engine for memory.

37:57.020 --> 37:57.860
We have the engine.

37:58.240 --> 38:01.160
But an engine sitting on a test block isn't a car.

38:01.160 --> 38:08.740
If you're building a real AI system, how does this beautiful, fluid, continuous, wave-based system

38:08.740 --> 38:13.300
actually interact with a standard, rigid AI model?

38:13.720 --> 38:14.960
That's the real challenge.

38:15.100 --> 38:17.560
How does it protect itself from garbage data?

38:17.680 --> 38:19.800
How does it actually maintain its archives?

38:20.060 --> 38:22.620
That is the crucial bridge we have to build next.

38:22.620 --> 38:30.260
We have to connect the sub-symbolic, our continuous fluid plenum field, with the symbolic...

38:30.260 --> 38:32.080
The standard discrete code.

38:32.140 --> 38:38.300
Right, the state compute output code that AI models like LLMs actually run on.

38:38.860 --> 38:45.380
The Flishan document refers to this as bridging the PsyForge layer with the IVERSE stack.

38:45.480 --> 38:48.980
Right, because standard AI code is entirely discrete.

38:48.980 --> 38:53.500
It operates on binary, uses symbols, tokens, strict state transitions.

38:54.340 --> 38:58.740
But our new memory plenum is made of continuous fields and interacting modes.

38:59.160 --> 39:01.680
If you just mash them together, you break both of them.

39:01.940 --> 39:04.500
You cannot conflate the ontologies of computation.

39:05.460 --> 39:08.280
A token in an LLM is not a wave in a field.

39:08.420 --> 39:09.680
So how do we bridge them?

39:09.860 --> 39:16.640
To safely bridge them, the RSVP framework introduces specific semantic grounding projection operators,

39:16.640 --> 39:19.440
denoted in the math as phi and psi.

39:19.800 --> 39:20.480
Phi and psi.

39:20.680 --> 39:24.640
Phi projects discrete symbolic data down into the continuous wave field.

39:25.060 --> 39:29.480
Psi projects the continuous wave excitations back up into discrete symbolic outputs.

39:29.860 --> 39:32.860
Now, the auto makes a really counterintuitive point here.

39:33.120 --> 39:37.840
When you project the data down into the waves, and then you project it back up into symbols,

39:37.840 --> 39:41.920
you do not get exactly 100% of the same data back.

